<DOC><DOCNO> AP880223-0267 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-02-23-88 2134EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-AppleLeak     02-23 0197</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Apple Leak,0203</SECOND><HEAD>Magazine Reveals Details of Long-Awaited Apple Product</HEAD><DATELINE>CUPERTINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A computer magazine has published astory providing confidential details of a long-awaited Applecomputer still under development.   The article appearing in this week's edition of Macintosh Todaywas based on a 160-page confidential in-house document given to afree-lance writer by an Apple employee, the San Francisco Examinersaid Tuesday.   The article details the size, appearance and technicalspecifications of Apple Computer Inc.'s Laguna laptop model, whichit said would be available in 1989.   Apple has been hard hit by information leaks before, and evenhired a private detective two years ago to find out who wasreleasing information. The investigator found leaks at firmsdeveloping software and accessories for Apple products, accordingto company spokeswoman Barbara Krause.   Ms. Krause declined to comment on the magazine report.   The article describes a 12-pound laptop capable of runningMacintosh software. It said the computer would have 1 megabyte ofinternal memory, the same as the Macintosh SE. It said the computerwould have a flat-panel screen and be powered by a five-poundlead-acid battery that will last up to 10 hours before recharging.</TEXT></DOC>